				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Recent Surge of Leveraged Loans Rattles Regulators</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Peter Eavis			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-05T00:20:15+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 4, 2014 7:20 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 4, 2014 7:20 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/05/business/dbpix-leverage-1/dbpix-leverage-1-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/05/business/dbpix-leverage-1/dbpix-leverage-1-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/05/business/dbpix-leverage-1/dbpix-leverage-1-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003216281" width="592" height="395" alt="Tom Shannon&#039;s chain of bowling alleys, Bowlmor AMF, is just one of many companies that have tapped the leveraged loan market."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Tom Shannon's chain of bowling alleys, Bowlmor AMF, is just one of many companies that have tapped the leveraged loan market.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Anthony Lanzilote for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/04/a-recent-surge-of-leveraged-loans-rattles-regulators/" data-title="A Recent Surge of Leveraged Loans Rattles Regulators" data-description="Regulators fear that the stampede into less conventional assets, including leveraged loans, could create bubbles that will later pop, harming banks and the wider economy. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/04/invesco-fund-treads-risky-path-as-major-investor-in-distressed-debt/">Invesco Fund Treads Risky Path as Major Investor in Distressed Debt </a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As regulators hunt for the next financial bubble, they are homing in on an obscure corner of Wall Street: the debt market where Tom Shannonâs company, a chain of flashy bowling alleys, recently borrowed nearly half a billion dollars.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Shannonâs company, Bowlmor AMF, is one of hundreds with unlovely balance sheets that have tapped this market for more than $2 trillion since the start of last year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt has all worked out very well for us,â Mr. Shannon said, sitting in the office of one of his bowling alleys, near Times Square. âThe payments are very reasonable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In raising money for Mr. Shannon, Wall Street would appear to be doing its job of matching companies that need capital with investors who can provide it. After banks like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation">Bank of America</a> make loans to the companies, they turn around and sell the debt to hedge funds, pensions and even mom-and-pop mutual funds. These leveraged loans, as the debt is known on Wall Street, funnel money to companies that might otherwise struggle to finance their ambitions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bank regulators, however, are worried.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent months, the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a> and the Officer of the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/c/comptroller_of_the_currency/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Comptroller of the Currency">Comptroller of the Currency</a> have intervened to tamp down the market. Leveraged loans are made to companies with low credit ratings that could suffer high losses in a downturn. As a result, the regulators have tried to stop the banks they regulate from arranging certain types of leveraged loan deals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Officials at both agencies contend that the crackdown is part of their core mission to ensure the safety and soundness of the banking system. But with this onslaught, they are also trying to have their regulatory cake and eat it, too.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fedâs policy of keeping interest rates at record lows has prompted investors to buy riskier and riskier investments to obtain some sort of return. The regulators fear that the stampede into less conventional assets, including leveraged loans, could create bubbles that will later pop, harming the banks and the wider economy. At the same time, however, the regulators are resistant to raising interest rates to curb such speculation. Instead, they have taken a targeted approach â and issued edicts directly into the leveraged loan market to limit the frothiness that they see there.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bankers who arrange the loan deals say that they are perplexed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In particular, they say that they do not understand why the regulators have focused their ire on leveraged loans. The amount of these loans is smaller than the total for junk bonds. And unlike junk bonds, leveraged loans are secured by the assets of the borrowing corporation, meaning that lenders often recover more when borrowers default.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Wall Street also fears that the regulatorsâ actions could turn out to be a heavy-handed overreaction that prevents companies from getting the capital they need.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhy would you mess with something that has worked pretty well for borrowers?â asked R. Bram Smith, executive director of the Loan Syndications and Trading Association, an industry group. âLeveraged loans have provided a lot of growth capital to some of the most dynamic sectors in the country, such as cable and cellular phones.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Shannon, for instance, said that in addition to paying off more expensive borrowings, AMF Bowlmor used the $410 million raised to acquire another bowling chain and for planned âcapital expendituresâ that aimed to refurbish some of its 338 outlets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt allows us to spend all we need in the way of capex,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What canât be denied, however, is that standards in the leveraged loan market have become much looser in recent years. The companies that have taken out the loans are on average much more indebted than in recent years. Companies that have done deals this year have debt that is 4.9 times as large as their annual cash flows, measured using earnings before subtracting expenses like interest, taxes and depreciation, according to data from <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/standard_and_poors/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Standard &#038; Poor's.">Standard &#038; Poorâs</a> Capital IQ. That multiple is up from 3.9 times in 2011 â and it is the same as the number for 2007, when the last boom in leveraged loans peaked.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This time around, however, one aspect of leveraged lending is much more aggressive. The special provisions within loan agreements that were once thought crucial for protecting creditors are fast disappearing. So far this year, 63 percent of leveraged loan deals lack such provisions, far higher than 25 percent in 2007, according to data from S.&#038;P. Capital IQ. âContractually, things are really at their weakest,â said Christina Padgett of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/moodys_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Moody's Investors Service.">Moodyâs Investors Service</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The low interest rates that followed the financial crisis effectively softened the blow of the last recession on the leveraged loan market. Borrowers that got into financial difficulty were often able to find lenders who would give them new loans. But credit analysts say that a future downturn may not be so kind. âThe next default cycle wonât look as good,â Ms. Padgett said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Seeing the deterioration, the bank regulators decided to move. Last year, they issued guidance that told banks that they had to have a strong grasp of the risks of leveraged loans and have the controls in place to manage them. The regulators also said that the banks needed to make sure the borrowing companies could work off their debt over the medium term. And, crucially, they said that deals by firms that had debt of over six times cash flows would raise concerns.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The regulatory action raised tensions on Wall Street. Bankers said the requirements were simplistic and could shut worthy borrowers out of the market. And the banks started to point fingers at each other when deals that seemed to fall afoul of regulatorsâ wishes got done.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sometimes these disputes pitted domestic banks against foreign lenders, like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=CS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Credit Suisse Group A.G">Credit Suisse</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DB&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Deutsche Bank AG">Deutsche Bank</a>, which have a large presence in the leveraged loan market. The bankers also became frustrated when it appeared that more loan deals were going to smaller firms, like Jefferies, that are subject to far less regulation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The agencies are expected to update their guidance imminently to clarify their intentions. But they are not expected to meaningfully soften their stance.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe combination of rapid growth and weak underwriting standards in the syndicated leveraged loan market, and the potential difficulty to refinance such deals in a more challenging environment, make leveraged lending a significant supervisory concern,â Darrin Benhart, a senior supervisor at the Comptroller of the Currency, said in an emailed statement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Shannon, who took over his first bowling alley in 1997, in Union Square, says that Bowlmor AMFâs new debt had not placed a big burden on the company. After the deal, the debt is equivalent to 3.4 times its cash flows.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThatâs a very comfortable level,â he said.</p>
